583.answer:
A URL query string is the part after `?` in a URL.

Example:

```text
https://example.com/search?q=hello%20world&page=2
```

Query string:

```text
q=hello%20world&page=2
```

It is usually made of `key=value` pairs separated by `&`.

- `q=hello%20world`
- `page=2`

## Percent-encoding

URLs can only safely contain certain characters directly. Other characters are encoded as `%` followed by two hexadecimal digits representing the byte value.

Examples:

- space → `%20`
- `&` → `%26`
- `=` → `%3D`
- `?` → `%3F`

So:

```text
hello world
```

becomes:

```text
hello%20world
```

This matters in query strings because characters like `&` and `=` have special meaning. If they appear inside actual data, they must be encoded.

Example:

```text
name=Tom%26Jerry
```

means the value is:

```text
Tom&Jerry
```

not two separate parameters.

## Parsing rules

A simple query string parser usually does this:

1. Remove a leading `?` if present.
2. Split the string on `&` to get pairs.
3. Split each pair on the first `=`.
4. Percent-decode the key and value.
5. Store them in a dictionary/object.

## Example implementation in JavaScript

```javascript
function parseQueryString(query) {
  const result = {};

  if (!query) return result;

  if (query.startsWith("?")) {
    query = query.slice(1);
  }

  if (!query) return result;

  for (const pair of query.split("&")) {
    if (!pair) continue;

    const eqIndex = pair.indexOf("=");
    let key, value;

    if (eqIndex === -1) {
      key = pair;
      value = "";
    } else {
      key = pair.slice(0, eqIndex);
      value = pair.slice(eqIndex + 1);
    }

    key = decodeURIComponent(key);
    value = decodeURIComponent(value);

    result[key] = value;
  }

  return result;
}
```

## Example usage

```javascript
console.log(parseQueryString("?q=hello%20world&page=2"));
// { q: "hello world", page: "2" }

console.log(parseQueryString("name=Tom%26Jerry"));
// { name: "Tom&Jerry" }

console.log(parseQueryString("flag"));
// { flag: "" }
```

## Note

If the same key appears multiple times:

```text
a=1&a=2
```

this version keeps the last value:

```javascript
{ a: "2" }
```

