A **greedy algorithm** builds a solution step by step, always making the locally optimal choice at each step.

### Core idea
Instead of exploring all possibilities like brute force or dynamic programming, greedy algorithms:
- make one choice at a time,
- never reconsider earlier choices,
- aim for a globally optimal result through good local decisions.

### When greedy works
A greedy strategy works only when the problem has:
- **Greedy-choice property**: a locally best choice can be part of a globally best solution.
- **Optimal substructure**: after making a choice, the remaining problem is still an optimal subproblem.

### Examples
- Activity selection
- Interval scheduling
- Huffman coding
- Kruskal’s and Prim’s MST algorithms
- Dijkstra’s algorithm (with non-negative weights)

### Advantages
- usually simple
- often fast
- low memory usage

### Disadvantage
- not always correct for every optimization problem

---

## Activity selection problem

Given activities with start and finish times, choose the **maximum number of non-overlapping intervals**.

### Greedy strategy
Pick the activity that **finishes earliest** first, then continue choosing the next activity whose start time is at least the finish time of the last chosen one.

### Why this works
Choosing the earliest finishing activity leaves the most room for future activities, so it maximizes how many can still fit afterward.

---

## C++ solution

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

using namespace std;

struct Activity {
    int start;
    int finish;
};

vector<Activity> selectActivities(vector<Activity> activities) {
    sort(activities.begin(), activities.end(), [](const Activity& a, const Activity& b) {
        if (a.finish == b.finish) {
            return a.start < b.start;
        }
        return a.finish < b.finish;
    });

    vector<Activity> selected;
    int lastFinish = -1;

    for (const auto& activity : activities) {
        if (activity.start >= lastFinish) {
            selected.push_back(activity);
            lastFinish = activity.finish;
        }
    }

    return selected;
}

int main() {
    vector<Activity> activities = {
        {1, 4},
        {3, 5},
        {0, 6},
        {5, 7},
        {8, 9},
        {5, 9}
    };

    vector<Activity> selected = selectActivities(activities);

    cout << "Maximum number of non-overlapping activities: "
         << selected.size() << "\n";

    cout << "Selected activities:\n";
    for (const auto& activity : selected) {
        cout << "(" << activity.start << ", " << activity.finish << ")\n";
    }

    return 0;
}
```

## Complexity
- **Sorting:** `O(n log n)`
- **Selection pass:** `O(n)`
- **Total:** `O(n log n)`

