Union-find, or **disjoint set union (DSU)**, is a data structure for tracking a collection of **non-overlapping sets**.

It supports two main operations efficiently:

- **find(x)**: returns the representative/root of the set containing `x`
- **union(a, b)**: merges the sets containing `a` and `b`

Typical use cases:

- checking whether two nodes are in the same connected component
- Kruskal’s algorithm for minimum spanning tree
- dynamic connectivity problems

## Core idea

Each set is represented as a **tree**:

- every element points to a parent
- the root points to itself
- the root is the set representative

### Naive problem
If trees get tall, `find` becomes slow.

### Optimizations

#### 1. Path compression
When calling `find(x)`, make every node on the path point directly to the root.

This flattens the tree over time.

#### 2. Union by rank
When merging two trees, attach the shorter/shallow tree under the taller one.

This keeps trees shallow.

Together, these make operations **almost constant time** in practice.

---

## JavaScript implementation

```js
class UnionFind {
  constructor(size) {
    this.parent = Array.from({ length: size }, (_, i) => i);
    this.rank = Array(size).fill(0);
  }

  find(x) {
    if (this.parent[x] !== x) {
      this.parent[x] = this.find(this.parent[x]); // path compression
    }
    return this.parent[x];
  }

  union(x, y) {
    const rootX = this.find(x);
    const rootY = this.find(y);

    if (rootX === rootY) {
      return false;
    }

    if (this.rank[rootX] < this.rank[rootY]) {
      this.parent[rootX] = rootY;
    } else if (this.rank[rootX] > this.rank[rootY]) {
      this.parent[rootY] = rootX;
    } else {
      this.parent[rootY] = rootX;
      this.rank[rootX]++;
    }

    return true;
  }

  connected(x, y) {
    return this.find(x) === this.find(y);
  }
}
```

---

## Example usage

```js
const uf = new UnionFind(7);

uf.union(0, 1);
uf.union(1, 2);
uf.union(3, 4);

console.log(uf.connected(0, 2)); // true
console.log(uf.connected(0, 4)); // false

uf.union(2, 4);

console.log(uf.connected(0, 4)); // true
```

---

## Complexity

With **path compression + union by rank**:

- `find`: amortized nearly O(1)
- `union`: amortized nearly O(1)

More formally, each operation is `O(α(n))`, where `α` is the inverse Ackermann function, which grows so slowly it’s effectively constant for real inputs.

