An AVL tree is a self-balancing binary search tree.

### Core idea
For every node, the heights of the left and right subtrees can differ by at most 1.

That difference is the **balance factor**:

```text
balanceFactor = height(left) - height(right)
```

Valid AVL balances are:
- `-1`
- `0`
- `1`

If insertion makes a node unbalanced, the tree is fixed with rotations.

### Why AVL trees matter
They keep the tree height at `O(log n)`, so operations stay efficient:
- Search: `O(log n)`
- Insert: `O(log n)`
- Delete: `O(log n)`

Without balancing, a BST can degrade to `O(n)`.

---

## Rotation cases after insertion

### 1. Left-Left (LL)
Inserted into the left subtree of the left child.  
Fix: **right rotation**

### 2. Right-Right (RR)
Inserted into the right subtree of the right child.  
Fix: **left rotation**

### 3. Left-Right (LR)
Inserted into the right subtree of the left child.  
Fix: **left rotation on left child**, then **right rotation**

### 4. Right-Left (RL)
Inserted into the left subtree of the right child.  
Fix: **right rotation on right child**, then **left rotation**

---

## Java implementation

```java
public class AVLTreeDemo {
    static class Node {
        int key;
        int height;
        Node left, right;

        Node(int key) {
            this.key = key;
            this.height = 1;
        }
    }

    static class AVLTree {
        Node root;

        int height(Node node) {
            return node == null ? 0 : node.height;
        }

        int getBalance(Node node) {
            return node == null ? 0 : height(node.left) - height(node.right);
        }

        Node rightRotate(Node y) {
            Node x = y.left;
            Node t2 = x.right;

            x.right = y;
            y.left = t2;

            y.height = 1 + Math.max(height(y.left), height(y.right));
            x.height = 1 + Math.max(height(x.left), height(x.right));

            return x;
        }

        Node leftRotate(Node x) {
            Node y = x.right;
            Node t2 = y.left;

            y.left = x;
            x.right = t2;

            x.height = 1 + Math.max(height(x.left), height(x.right));
            y.height = 1 + Math.max(height(y.left), height(y.right));

            return y;
        }

        Node insert(Node node, int key) {
            if (node == null) {
                return new Node(key);
            }

            if (key < node.key) {
                node.left = insert(node.left, key);
            } else if (key > node.key) {
                node.right = insert(node.right, key);
            } else {
                return node;
            }

            node.height = 1 + Math.max(height(node.left), height(node.right));
            int balance = getBalance(node);

            if (balance > 1 && key < node.left.key) {
                return rightRotate(node);
            }

            if (balance < -1 && key > node.right.key) {
                return leftRotate(node);
            }

            if (balance > 1 && key > node.left.key) {
                node.left = leftRotate(node.left);
                return rightRotate(node);
            }

            if (balance < -1 && key < node.right.key) {
                node.right = rightRotate(node.right);
                return leftRotate(node);
            }

            return node;
        }

        void insert(int key) {
            root = insert(root, key);
        }

        void inorder(Node node) {
            if (node != null) {
                inorder(node.left);
                System.out.print(node.key + " ");
                inorder(node.right);
            }
        }

        void printInOrder() {
            inorder(root);
            System.out.println();
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        AVLTree tree = new AVLTree();
        int[] values = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 25};

        for (int value : values) {
            tree.insert(value);
        }

        System.out.print("In-order traversal: ");
        tree.printInOrder();
    }
}
```

---

## Output

```text
In-order traversal: 10 20 25 30 40 50
```

That output is sorted because in-order traversal of any BST, including an AVL tree, visits keys in ascending order.

