I'll inspect the repo for any existing C# files or logging conventions first.No C# code exists here, so I'll add a minimal example file.The **singleton pattern** ensures a class has **exactly one instance** and provides a **global access point** to it.

### When it’s useful
Use it when your app should share one coordinated object, like:
- a logger
- configuration manager
- cache
- connection manager

### Core characteristics
A singleton usually has:
- a **private constructor** so no other code can create instances directly
- a **static field** to store the single instance
- a **public static accessor** like `GetInstance()`

### Thread safety
In multithreaded apps, two threads could try to create the instance at the same time. A thread-safe singleton prevents that with synchronization, usually with:
- `lock`
- `Lazy<T>`
- static initialization

I implemented a simple **thread-safe singleton logger** here:

- `SingletonLogger.cs:1`

It uses:
- **double-checked locking** for singleton creation
- a separate **write lock** so file writes are thread-safe

### Implementation
```csharp
using System;
using System.IO;
using System.Threading;

public sealed class SingletonLogger
{
    private static SingletonLogger? _instance;
    private static readonly object InstanceLock = new();

    private readonly object _writeLock = new();
    private readonly string _logFilePath;

    private SingletonLogger(string logFilePath)
    {
        _logFilePath = logFilePath;
    }

    public static SingletonLogger GetInstance(string logFilePath = "app.log")
    {
        if (_instance == null)
        {
            lock (InstanceLock)
            {
                if (_instance == null)
                {
                    _instance = new SingletonLogger(logFilePath);
                }
            }
        }

        return _instance;
    }

    public void Log(string message)
    {
        var logEntry = $"[{DateTime.UtcNow:O}] [Thread {Thread.CurrentThread.ManagedThreadId}] {message}{Environment.NewLine}";

        lock (_writeLock)
        {
            File.AppendAllText(_logFilePath, logEntry);
        }
    }
}

public static class Program
{
    public static void Main()
    {
        var logger = SingletonLogger.GetInstance("application.log");
        logger.Log("Application started.");

        var sameLogger = SingletonLogger.GetInstance();
        sameLogger.Log("This uses the same singleton instance.");
    }
}
```

### Important note
With this design, the **first** call to `GetInstance(...)` decides the log file path for the lifetime of the app.

